  headline="Missed Call Text Back for UK Driveway & Paving Contractors"
  accentWord="Driveway & Paving"
  subhead="You are operating a plate compactor on a block paving driveway when a developer calls about paving a communal parking area. A text goes out in five seconds — the contract stays warm."
  scenario="It is 3:40pm on a Saturday in May. You have been installing a resin-bound driveway at a bungalow in Carterton since 8am — the final pour is complete, the surface is trowelled smooth, and you are waiting for initial cure before edging. Your phone is in the van and has two missed calls during the afternoon pour. Without Missed Call Text Back, you check the phone at 4pm. One voicemail is a homeowner in Witney — 'Hi, wanting a new driveway, give me a ring' — no name, no details. The other is a blank voicemail from an unknown number. You call the first number back at 4:15 but it goes to voicemail. The unknown number gives you nothing. Both leads are gone. With Missed Call Text Back, the Witney caller received a text six seconds after the missed call at 2:20pm: 'Thank you for calling [your company]. We are on a driveway installation and will call you back today. Reply with your requirements for a faster response.' She replied at 2:25pm: 'Hi, we have a gravel drive that floods every winter — about 55sqm. Want block paving. Can you come and look this week? We are in OX28.' The unknown number also received the text and replied: 'Need a price for resurfacing my tarmac drive, about 30sqm, Carterton.' At 4pm you check your phone and find two complete lead summaries: a 55sqm gravel-to-block conversion in Witney with flooding issues, and a 30sqm tarmac resurface literally in the same town where you are working today. You call both back within minutes."
  benefits={benefits}
  faqs={faqs}
  channelPageUrl="/construction-trades/missed-call-text-back/"
  tradePageUrl="/driveway-paving/ai-receptionist/"
  ctaHeadline="Stop Losing Peak-Season Driveway Leads to Missed Calls"
